# {{WORKER_DISPLAY_NAME}} — authoring notes

This is the rationale layer for the worker. It exists so a future reforge can pick up enough context to make a confident change without re-interviewing the user. It's allowed to read like notes — `WORKER.md` is the clean version.

## Original ask

What the user said in their own words. Paste it verbatim.

## Restatement

The one-paragraph spec you read back to the user and they confirmed.

## CODE-first alternatives considered

Cases where the task seemed to need a LOCAL or HOSTED unit and you proposed a CODE shape instead. For each: what you proposed, what the user said, why you accepted or rejected the CODE shape. (If every unit was obvious, this section is short — say so.)

## Interview answers

- **Worker name (slug):** the kebab-case identifier used for the workspace folder and the `name:` field in `WORKER.md`.
- **Display name:** the human-readable name used in window titles, the about box, `WORKER.md`'s `# Heading`, and the artifact filename in `dist/` (e.g. `Manga Katana Watcher.exe`, not `manga-katana-watcher.exe`).
- **Target OS:** windows / macos / linux (multi-select if more than one).
- **Trigger style:** double-click / CLI / GUI (mutually exclusive: double-click vs. GUI).
- **Icon:** default / user-provided (path to the file the user supplied, dropped into `resources/`).
- **Scheduling:** none / loop while running / start on boot / external scheduler (list whichever applies; multi-select allowed).
- **UI framework:** native (Tkinter / SwiftUI / WinUI) / other (which?) / N/A.
- **Color theme:** dark / light / user-provided (palette) / N/A if no GUI.
- **Data storage format:** sqlite / json / text / user-provided.
- **Data location:** worker dir / home dir / mounted drive / user-provided path.
- **Local models used:** list each LOCAL unit and the model picked (e.g., "summarize → llama3.2:3b").
- **Hosted providers used:** list each HOSTED unit and the provider/model picked.
- **Bundled local-model setup script:** yes / no.
- **Hosted-model auth strategy:** OS keyring / env var / config file.

## Decisions and the reasoning

For each non-obvious choice, write a sentence or two on what you picked and why. Examples that future-you will want to see:

- "Picked JSON over SQLite for storage because the worker only writes a single timestamp per run; SQLite would be overkill."
- "Picked LOCAL `llama3.2:3b` for the summary unit because the input is always one short article and the user explicitly said they don't want hosted dependencies."
- "Picked PyInstaller over Nuitka for the Windows build to keep build times reasonable."

## Alternatives considered and rejected

Things you thought about and chose not to do. The discipline is to write these down even when the rejected option is dumb — future-you may be considering exactly that dumb option and the note saves the re-derivation.

## Edge cases the user signed off on

What the worker does when:

- The input is empty.
- Output already exists (overwrite / append / suffix / fail).
- Partial failure (one of N sources is down).
- It's the first run (initialization, baseline fetch).
- It's run twice in a row (idempotent or not).

